WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.660
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:03.660 --> 00:00:05.410
SHARON SALZBERG: Great,
thank you so much.

00:00:05.410 --> 00:00:07.140
It's such a delight to be here.

00:00:07.140 --> 00:00:10.990
I was here a little bit for
this conference, Wisdom 2.0,

00:00:10.990 --> 00:00:13.250
so it was kind of
nice coming back

00:00:13.250 --> 00:00:16.149
into the same room and
just sort of settling.

00:00:16.149 --> 00:00:21.890
So I as you doubtless know,
I am a meditation teacher.

00:00:21.890 --> 00:00:25.140
And its very funny now when I'm
introduced that way, because I

00:00:25.140 --> 00:00:28.290
came back from India where
I'd first gone to study--

00:00:28.290 --> 00:00:32.098
I went in 1970, and
came back in 1974.

00:00:32.098 --> 00:00:36.135
And in those days, I'd be at a
party or some social situation

00:00:36.135 --> 00:00:39.000
and people would say
to me, what do you do?

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:41.360
And I'd say, I teach meditation.

00:00:41.360 --> 00:00:44.360
And they would kind of
go, oh, that's weird.

00:00:44.360 --> 00:00:46.610
Or occasionally, somebody
would say to me, oh,

00:00:46.610 --> 00:00:49.170
did you meet the Beatles
when you were over there.

00:00:49.170 --> 00:00:51.920
I'd say, sadly no, they went
when I was in high school.

00:00:51.920 --> 00:00:56.890
And now, all these years later--
after so much more significant

00:00:56.890 --> 00:01:01.280
research, and science,
and kind of a relanguaging

00:01:01.280 --> 00:01:04.459
of the whole process--
the most common response

00:01:04.459 --> 00:01:07.730
I hear when I say
teach meditation is,

00:01:07.730 --> 00:01:09.360
I'm so stressed out.

00:01:09.360 --> 00:01:12.100
I could really use some of that.

00:01:12.100 --> 00:01:15.060
Although my favorite response,
which I also hear sometimes

00:01:15.060 --> 00:01:17.320
is-- my partner should
really meet you,

00:01:17.320 --> 00:01:19.790
that'd be really good for them.

00:01:19.790 --> 00:01:24.460
And these days, even going
beyond the context of stress,

00:01:24.460 --> 00:01:27.550
people see meditation--
I think rightly so--

00:01:27.550 --> 00:01:29.100
as a kind of capacity building.

00:01:29.100 --> 00:01:31.760
As a way of finding
resourcefulness,

00:01:31.760 --> 00:01:35.270
and a kind of an innovative
energy within themselves.

00:01:35.270 --> 00:01:40.080
Sometimes I hear the
response which concerns me

00:01:40.080 --> 00:01:44.150
the most, which is, oh I tried
that once, I failed at it.

00:01:44.150 --> 00:01:45.330
I couldn't do it.

00:01:45.330 --> 00:01:48.050
And then what follows
is some description

00:01:48.050 --> 00:01:51.640
of what people expect.

00:01:51.640 --> 00:01:53.800
I should be able to
stop all my thinking.

00:01:53.800 --> 00:01:56.200
I should have a
completely blank mind.

00:01:56.200 --> 00:01:58.460
I should have only
beautiful thoughts,

00:01:58.460 --> 00:02:01.220
like doubtless everyone
else in the room is having.

00:02:01.220 --> 00:02:05.460
I should be able to keep
sleepiness completely at bay.

00:02:05.460 --> 00:02:08.539
I should find perfect peace
within the first hour.

00:02:08.539 --> 00:02:10.039
Whatever it might be.

00:02:10.039 --> 00:02:14.120
And that of course concerns me,
because we say we believe very

00:02:14.120 --> 00:02:16.010
strongly, you cannot fail at it.

00:02:16.010 --> 00:02:18.430
It's impossible.

00:02:18.430 --> 00:02:22.220
Because the essence of
the meditative process

00:02:22.220 --> 00:02:25.980
is changing the way we
relate to everything.

00:02:25.980 --> 00:02:28.260
So it's that quality
of relationship,

00:02:28.260 --> 00:02:30.560
that's where the
transformation takes place.

00:02:30.560 --> 00:02:33.920
So you can't actually be
having the wrong experience,

00:02:33.920 --> 00:02:35.880
the wrong thing happening.

00:02:35.880 --> 00:02:38.490
So I'd gone to
India to begin with.

00:02:38.490 --> 00:02:42.850
It was actually my
junior year in college.

00:02:42.850 --> 00:02:44.780
I went to college when I was 16.

00:02:44.780 --> 00:02:47.290
I'm a product of the New York
City public school system

00:02:47.290 --> 00:02:51.150
where they like to skip grades,
so I skipped two grades.

00:02:51.150 --> 00:02:53.520
And when I was a
sophomore in college,

00:02:53.520 --> 00:02:55.270
I took an Asian
philosophy course--

00:02:55.270 --> 00:03:00.930
which quite honestly, as I look
back, was sort of happenstance.

00:03:00.930 --> 00:03:02.480
I needed a philosophy course.

00:03:02.480 --> 00:03:04.330
It was a requirement.

00:03:04.330 --> 00:03:06.590
I looked at the schedule,
and it was something

00:03:06.590 --> 00:03:10.760
like-- it's on Tuesday,
that would be convenient,

00:03:10.760 --> 00:03:11.910
so let me take that.

00:03:11.910 --> 00:03:14.690
And of course the course
completely changed my life.

00:03:14.690 --> 00:03:18.560
So this is what I
heard in that context.

00:03:18.560 --> 00:03:21.360
That there were
some very practical,

00:03:21.360 --> 00:03:24.830
immediate, direct
tools that anybody

00:03:24.830 --> 00:03:26.490
could do if they want to.

00:03:26.490 --> 00:03:29.580
There wasn't, like,
a prerequisite.

00:03:29.580 --> 00:03:32.990
Anybody who wished to
could pick them up,

00:03:32.990 --> 00:03:35.500
and that these
tools of meditation

00:03:35.500 --> 00:03:38.320
were like skills training.

00:03:38.320 --> 00:03:41.300
Training, first of
all, in concentration.

00:03:41.300 --> 00:03:45.280
In the ability to
stabilize our attention.

00:03:45.280 --> 00:03:48.350
Most of us experience
ourselves as fairly distracted,

00:03:48.350 --> 00:03:51.980
maybe not in every
realm of our experience,

00:03:51.980 --> 00:03:53.730
but at least in some.

00:03:53.730 --> 00:03:57.850
Where we sit down to think
something through, or work

00:03:57.850 --> 00:04:00.380
through a dilemma,
and then we're gone.

00:04:00.380 --> 00:04:02.670
The way our minds tend
to jump to the past,

00:04:02.670 --> 00:04:06.140
and we go over and over and
over some situation, often one

00:04:06.140 --> 00:04:10.127
where we now have some
kind of tinge of regret.

00:04:10.127 --> 00:04:12.210
I should've said nothing,
I should have said more.

00:04:12.210 --> 00:04:15.410
Why did I go there, why
didn't I, why did I stay?

00:04:15.410 --> 00:04:17.029
Whatever it is.

00:04:17.029 --> 00:04:19.029
And we don't go
over it with an eye

00:04:19.029 --> 00:04:21.649
toward making amends, or
learning from our mistakes.

00:04:21.649 --> 00:04:25.732
We just go over it, and over
it, and over it, and over it.

00:04:25.732 --> 00:04:28.370
Or our minds jump to
the future, and we

00:04:28.370 --> 00:04:32.930
create a scenario that has not
happened, and may never happen.

00:04:32.930 --> 00:04:35.470
Which is different that just
kind of creating a space,

00:04:35.470 --> 00:04:37.580
and letting your mind roam.

00:04:37.580 --> 00:04:40.794
It's more like an anxiety
driven construct-- of like,

00:04:40.794 --> 00:04:42.210
well then this is
going to happen,

00:04:42.210 --> 00:04:43.390
and that's going to happen.

00:04:43.390 --> 00:04:46.310
No doubt it will all fall
apart when that happens.

00:04:46.310 --> 00:04:48.550
And then we emerge
from that with kind

00:04:48.550 --> 00:04:50.550
of the burden of that.

00:04:50.550 --> 00:04:53.590
So our minds tend to jump to
the past, jump to the future.

00:04:53.590 --> 00:04:54.100
Judgement.

00:04:54.100 --> 00:04:55.640
Speculation.

00:04:55.640 --> 00:04:59.370
And the process of
developing concentration

00:04:59.370 --> 00:05:03.000
is one of more
stabilizing our attention.

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:05.690
It's not in a frozen way,
it's not in a rigid way.

00:05:05.690 --> 00:05:09.590
But it's like with tremendous
flexibility and fluidity.

00:05:09.590 --> 00:05:12.130
So we realize we're
gone, we can come back.

00:05:12.130 --> 00:05:16.440
So that the end result is
that we're much more centered,

00:05:16.440 --> 00:05:18.080
and grounded, and present.

00:05:18.080 --> 00:05:20.500
And we recapture
all that energy,

00:05:20.500 --> 00:05:23.150
which has been just
flying all over the place.

00:05:23.150 --> 00:05:25.550
The larger consequence,
the feeling

00:05:25.550 --> 00:05:27.800
of that sort of
distraction is said

00:05:27.800 --> 00:05:29.920
to be a kind of fragmentation.

00:05:29.920 --> 00:05:33.390
It's the way we have so
much role identification

00:05:33.390 --> 00:05:34.550
often in this society.

00:05:34.550 --> 00:05:37.540
That people say, I feel
like I'm one person at work,

00:05:37.540 --> 00:05:39.830
and I'm a different
person at home.

00:05:39.830 --> 00:05:41.650
Or my very favorite
example of that

00:05:41.650 --> 00:05:45.650
still is, I was teaching
in New York City somewhere.

00:05:45.650 --> 00:05:47.540
And somebody raised
her hand and she said,

00:05:47.540 --> 00:05:50.260
I feel filled with loving
kindness and compassion

00:05:50.260 --> 00:05:53.540
for all beings everywhere,
as long as I'm alone.

00:05:53.540 --> 00:05:56.609
But once I'm with others,
it's really rough.

00:05:56.609 --> 00:05:58.150
And everybody laughed,
because we all

00:05:58.150 --> 00:06:00.802
knew exactly what she meant.

00:06:00.802 --> 00:06:02.260
And it can be the
other way around.

00:06:02.260 --> 00:06:04.130
We might feel fine
when we're with others,

00:06:04.130 --> 00:06:06.330
and very ill at
ease being alone.

00:06:06.330 --> 00:06:08.720
So our lives can
be very cut apart.

00:06:08.720 --> 00:06:10.120
Or seem very cut apart.

00:06:10.120 --> 00:06:14.060
Whereas the reality is
that they're seamless.

00:06:14.060 --> 00:06:16.600
We're of one piece.

00:06:16.600 --> 00:06:20.360
So concentration and a greater
stabilization of attention

00:06:20.360 --> 00:06:24.090
is one of the great
skills of meditation.

00:06:24.090 --> 00:06:27.510
The second is mindfulness,
which for me feels

00:06:27.510 --> 00:06:29.140
kind of like the
word of the hour.

00:06:29.140 --> 00:06:30.764
When I came back from
India, of course,

00:06:30.764 --> 00:06:32.660
no one ever use the
word mindfulness,

00:06:32.660 --> 00:06:35.810
unless you were using it in a
very kind of classical context

00:06:35.810 --> 00:06:38.400
in terms of meditation training.

00:06:38.400 --> 00:06:41.580
And now it's just everywhere.

00:06:41.580 --> 00:06:43.850
I teach in Washington,
DC about once a month,

00:06:43.850 --> 00:06:48.380
and one of my great amusements
is listening to the conductors.

00:06:48.380 --> 00:06:50.120
Because every once
in awhile they

00:06:50.120 --> 00:06:55.050
will say please be mindful
of the gap between the train

00:06:55.050 --> 00:06:57.560
and the station platform,
and I get very excited.

00:06:57.560 --> 00:06:59.810
I'm like, oh they said mindful.

00:06:59.810 --> 00:07:01.850
Mostly they say what
they really mean,

00:07:01.850 --> 00:07:04.750
which is please be
careful of the gap.

00:07:04.750 --> 00:07:08.380
I recently had the conductor
who simply said, there's a gap.

00:07:08.380 --> 00:07:11.930
It's like, no hint about how
he wanted you to relate to it.

00:07:11.930 --> 00:07:15.040
It's just like, there it is.

00:07:15.040 --> 00:07:17.420
But really, you hear this
word like everywhere now.

00:07:17.420 --> 00:07:22.280
So classically, mindfulness
means a quality of awareness.

00:07:22.280 --> 00:07:25.960
A way of paying attention so
that our perception of what's

00:07:25.960 --> 00:07:30.070
happening in the moment is
not so distorted by bias.

00:07:30.070 --> 00:07:32.320
Projection into the
future, like what's this

00:07:32.320 --> 00:07:36.000
going to feel like in three
months, eight months, 10

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:37.290
years, right?

00:07:37.290 --> 00:07:40.750
Which distorts our sense of
what's happening right now.

00:07:40.750 --> 00:07:44.510
And interestingly enough,
as an example of that,

00:07:44.510 --> 00:07:48.370
in some of the meditation
research around physical pain

00:07:48.370 --> 00:07:51.570
what they've
discovered-- and this

00:07:51.570 --> 00:07:56.870
is Richie Davidson's lab
in Madison, Wisconsin.

00:07:56.870 --> 00:08:00.450
I don't know how they got
IRB approval to inflict pain,

00:08:00.450 --> 00:08:02.030
but somehow they did.

00:08:02.030 --> 00:08:06.660
And what they discovered
was that the difference

00:08:06.660 --> 00:08:09.900
between meditators
and non-meditators

00:08:09.900 --> 00:08:11.550
was not the reaction
to the pain.

00:08:11.550 --> 00:08:15.050
Everybody had the
reaction to pain.

00:08:15.050 --> 00:08:18.460
But the difference was in
terms of what happened next,

00:08:18.460 --> 00:08:22.380
where they said
non-meditators tended

00:08:22.380 --> 00:08:25.410
to flip into an
anticipatory cycle.

00:08:25.410 --> 00:08:28.780
It's like, whatever happened
in terms of the pain,

00:08:28.780 --> 00:08:31.260
you know the tension,
the reaction, happened.

00:08:31.260 --> 00:08:34.360
But then they didn't
relax subsequent to that.

00:08:34.360 --> 00:08:37.767
Because they were very caught up
in when's the next bout coming.

00:08:37.767 --> 00:08:38.850
How bad is it going to be.

00:08:38.850 --> 00:08:40.179
How intense will be.

00:08:40.179 --> 00:08:40.679
Right?

00:08:40.679 --> 00:08:45.380
Whereas the meditators have that
same reaction to pain, but then

00:08:45.380 --> 00:08:46.960
it was over.

00:08:46.960 --> 00:08:49.500
And they weren't caught in
all of that anticipation.

00:08:49.500 --> 00:08:51.450
It's interesting.

00:08:51.450 --> 00:08:54.220
So maybe that is
a great tendency,

00:08:54.220 --> 00:08:58.850
or we just pile on to our
experience in some way,

00:08:58.850 --> 00:09:03.370
but we're continually adding so
many layers of interpretation

00:09:03.370 --> 00:09:05.890
and judgment that we
lose touch with what

00:09:05.890 --> 00:09:08.890
is actually happening right now.

00:09:08.890 --> 00:09:11.530
Or, we have a big
thing about control.

00:09:11.530 --> 00:09:13.035
I shouldn't be feeling this way.

00:09:13.035 --> 00:09:13.995
This is here.

00:09:13.995 --> 00:09:15.940
I've been meditating
for 40 years.

00:09:15.940 --> 00:09:17.460
It shouldn't be here anymore.

00:09:17.460 --> 00:09:21.280
Or I spent $10,000 in
therapy just last year,

00:09:21.280 --> 00:09:23.075
surely it should be gone.

00:09:23.075 --> 00:09:25.510
Or no one else feels this.

00:09:25.510 --> 00:09:27.290
Or whatever it might be.

00:09:27.290 --> 00:09:30.960
All of which tends to distort
the actual experience.

00:09:30.960 --> 00:09:35.120
And so we say that
mindfulness is the ability

00:09:35.120 --> 00:09:40.880
to make the distinction between
what our direct experience is,

00:09:40.880 --> 00:09:42.670
and then everything
we make of it.

00:09:42.670 --> 00:09:46.130
It's not to say we want
to destroy or annihilate

00:09:46.130 --> 00:09:47.620
that narrative capacity.

00:09:47.620 --> 00:09:49.600
We want that, for sure.

00:09:49.600 --> 00:09:52.970
But we don't necessarily
want to be stuck there.

00:09:52.970 --> 00:09:54.110
Right?

00:09:54.110 --> 00:09:56.410
We might want more to
be able to see things

00:09:56.410 --> 00:09:59.580
from different angles, and
see them for ourselves.

00:09:59.580 --> 00:10:02.440
Just in the
interests of freedom.

00:10:02.440 --> 00:10:04.170
So my favorite
example of mindfulness

00:10:04.170 --> 00:10:07.820
these days is, let's say
you're on your way to a party.

00:10:07.820 --> 00:10:11.410
And you run into a friend,
and the friend says to you,

00:10:11.410 --> 00:10:13.600
you know who I met today?

00:10:13.600 --> 00:10:16.540
That new person who's
going to be our colleague,

00:10:16.540 --> 00:10:19.730
and they're really,
really, really boring.

00:10:19.730 --> 00:10:21.890
And then you go to the
party, and who do you end up

00:10:21.890 --> 00:10:24.720
stuck talking to you,
but the very person

00:10:24.720 --> 00:10:27.010
you have just been told is
like the most boring person

00:10:27.010 --> 00:10:27.510
on earth.

00:10:30.560 --> 00:10:33.120
Very likely, you don't
really listen to them.

00:10:33.120 --> 00:10:34.370
You don't really look at them.

00:10:34.370 --> 00:10:36.630
You're thinking about the
50 emails you need to send,

00:10:36.630 --> 00:10:40.050
or everybody else you'd
rather be talking to

00:10:40.050 --> 00:10:42.360
than this very person.

00:10:42.360 --> 00:10:46.590
But sometimes we realize
that, and we stop,

00:10:46.590 --> 00:10:50.610
and we gather our attention,
and we do really listen.

00:10:50.610 --> 00:10:53.480
And we really look.

00:10:53.480 --> 00:10:57.170
Maybe we come to the end of that
party and we walk out thinking,

00:10:57.170 --> 00:10:59.570
you know that new person?

00:10:59.570 --> 00:11:02.290
They are so boring.

00:11:02.290 --> 00:11:04.110
But maybe we don't.

00:11:04.110 --> 00:11:05.910
Because life is
full of surprises

00:11:05.910 --> 00:11:07.540
when we pay attention.

00:11:07.540 --> 00:11:09.760
So why take a borrowed
impression, what

00:11:09.760 --> 00:11:13.670
someone else said about
something or someone,

00:11:13.670 --> 00:11:17.710
rather than developing our
capacity to realize that.

00:11:17.710 --> 00:11:21.050
Let go of some of those
preconceptions and assumptions.

00:11:21.050 --> 00:11:24.510
See more directly, and
decide for ourselves.

00:11:24.510 --> 00:11:26.680
So one of the great
dangers of mindfulness

00:11:26.680 --> 00:11:29.790
in terms of the language that
we tend to use around it,

00:11:29.790 --> 00:11:31.354
is that it can seem so passive.

00:11:31.354 --> 00:11:32.145
It's so complacent.

00:11:34.950 --> 00:11:36.310
Or so it seems.

00:11:36.310 --> 00:11:38.290
Of course, it doesn't really.

00:11:38.290 --> 00:11:40.440
When we say things
like, mindfulness

00:11:40.440 --> 00:11:42.560
means accepting things
the way that they are,

00:11:42.560 --> 00:11:46.320
it sounds like you're
going to vegetate.

00:11:46.320 --> 00:11:48.730
Or, be with your experience
without judgment,

00:11:48.730 --> 00:11:50.440
that you're going
to lose discernment

00:11:50.440 --> 00:11:52.830
and an edge of activity.

00:11:52.830 --> 00:11:55.070
And of course, it's
not like that at all.

00:11:55.070 --> 00:11:57.490
It's much more
creating that space.

00:11:57.490 --> 00:12:00.220
That our action
is comprehensive.

00:12:00.220 --> 00:12:04.090
It's not coming from someone
else's vision of what's true.

00:12:04.090 --> 00:12:08.000
That we can make
choice very easily.

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:10.100
We're going to do just a
little bit of meditation

00:12:10.100 --> 00:12:15.720
here together, and one of the
standard kind of beginnings

00:12:15.720 --> 00:12:20.340
to a meditation instruction
is to sit and just

00:12:20.340 --> 00:12:21.200
listen to sound.

00:12:21.200 --> 00:12:22.741
Of course, there's
not a lot of sound

00:12:22.741 --> 00:12:26.420
here, but I'll make
some just by talking.

00:12:26.420 --> 00:12:30.040
I once gave that
instruction somewhere,

00:12:30.040 --> 00:12:32.000
and immediately someone
raised their hand

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:35.110
and said, well, what if it's
the sound of the smoke alarm

00:12:35.110 --> 00:12:35.610
I hear.

00:12:35.610 --> 00:12:37.560
Am I supposed to sit
here mindfully knowing

00:12:37.560 --> 00:12:39.830
that the smoke
alarm is going off?

00:12:39.830 --> 00:12:41.390
Or should I get up?

00:12:41.390 --> 00:12:43.410
And I said, I'd get up.

00:12:43.410 --> 00:12:46.850
All right.

00:12:46.850 --> 00:12:49.540
But I can see how one
can have that impression.

00:12:49.540 --> 00:12:53.640
And yet, really the relationship
of mindfulness to whatever

00:12:53.640 --> 00:12:56.820
we're experiencing-- something
very vital, and alive,

00:12:56.820 --> 00:12:59.800
and creative because
we're freeing ourselves

00:12:59.800 --> 00:13:03.490
from all of those old
habits of perception.

00:13:03.490 --> 00:13:07.420
And then the last great skill of
meditation practice, the third,

00:13:07.420 --> 00:13:09.990
is compassion.

00:13:09.990 --> 00:13:11.200
Or loving kindness.

00:13:11.200 --> 00:13:12.530
Compassion for ourselves.

00:13:12.530 --> 00:13:14.419
Compassion for others.

00:13:14.419 --> 00:13:15.960
And this is a very
interesting thing.

00:13:15.960 --> 00:13:20.890
First of all, the notion that
compassion can be trained

00:13:20.890 --> 00:13:24.550
is a little weird,
I find, in the West.

00:13:24.550 --> 00:13:27.230
People think of it as
cold and mechanistic,

00:13:27.230 --> 00:13:28.890
whereas in the
Eastern psychology,

00:13:28.890 --> 00:13:31.620
say in Buddhist
psychology, absolutely

00:13:31.620 --> 00:13:34.430
it's considered that
compassion can be trained,

00:13:34.430 --> 00:13:37.430
because we know that
attention can be trained.

00:13:37.430 --> 00:13:39.780
And compassion is like
an emergent property

00:13:39.780 --> 00:13:42.160
of how we pay attention.

00:13:42.160 --> 00:13:47.020
How do we recover when
we've made a mistake.

00:13:47.020 --> 00:13:50.070
When we've lost sight
of our aspiration.

00:13:50.070 --> 00:13:52.420
When we've strayed
from our chosen course.

00:13:52.420 --> 00:13:54.840
And the kind of
mini version of that

00:13:54.840 --> 00:13:57.880
is inherent in the
meditation instruction.

00:13:57.880 --> 00:13:59.010
You sit down.

00:13:59.010 --> 00:14:00.790
You have an object
of awareness, say

00:14:00.790 --> 00:14:02.480
it's the feeling of
the breath, which

00:14:02.480 --> 00:14:04.860
is what we're going to do.

00:14:04.860 --> 00:14:08.940
And most people discover
it's not 900 breaths

00:14:08.940 --> 00:14:11.080
before their attention wonders.

00:14:11.080 --> 00:14:13.870
Usually it's more like three.

00:14:13.870 --> 00:14:15.670
Or maybe five, or maybe eight.

00:14:15.670 --> 00:14:17.030
Maybe one.

00:14:17.030 --> 00:14:17.930
And then we're gone.

00:14:17.930 --> 00:14:20.820
And sometimes we are way gone.

00:14:20.820 --> 00:14:25.990
And then comes this magic
moment when we realize oh, it's

00:14:25.990 --> 00:14:28.830
been quite some time since
I last felt a breath.

00:14:28.830 --> 00:14:33.030
That's the moment where instead
of the berating ourselves,

00:14:33.030 --> 00:14:36.020
and chastising ourselves,
and feeling like a failure.

00:14:36.020 --> 00:14:40.730
We practice letting go, with
practice beginning again.

00:14:40.730 --> 00:14:42.730
And the only way
we can do that is

00:14:42.730 --> 00:14:44.800
to deepen compassion
for ourselves.

00:14:44.800 --> 00:14:46.970
And this is very
interesting also,

00:14:46.970 --> 00:14:50.200
because I was teaching
somewhere very recently,

00:14:50.200 --> 00:14:54.885
and someone raised their hand
and said, I don't buy that.

00:14:54.885 --> 00:14:57.740
You know, I think if you
have compassion for yourself,

00:14:57.740 --> 00:15:00.450
in effect, if you
forgive yourself,

00:15:00.450 --> 00:15:02.580
that it just makes you lazy.

00:15:02.580 --> 00:15:06.000
That you're going to give
up a sense of clarity

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:08.250
about ambition, or goal.

00:15:08.250 --> 00:15:11.470
And that you're just going
to let yourself do anything.

00:15:11.470 --> 00:15:13.900
But I don't honestly buy that.

00:15:13.900 --> 00:15:17.800
Because I think if we look
at how we learn, how we grow,

00:15:17.800 --> 00:15:22.350
how we change, it's
usually not from that kind

00:15:22.350 --> 00:15:25.060
of brutal self-judgment.

00:15:25.060 --> 00:15:29.460
So just in the example
of the meditation,

00:15:29.460 --> 00:15:34.620
you sit down to feel the breath.

00:15:34.620 --> 00:15:39.180
It is one breath,
and then you're gone.

00:15:39.180 --> 00:15:40.490
It's not that useful.

00:15:40.490 --> 00:15:41.490
It's not that efficient.

00:15:41.490 --> 00:15:44.260
It's not that
effective to realize

00:15:44.260 --> 00:15:46.020
that you've been
distracted and then

00:15:46.020 --> 00:15:48.840
launch into this spiral
of self-judgment.

00:15:48.840 --> 00:15:50.280
I can't believe I'm thinking.

00:15:50.280 --> 00:15:51.910
No one else in the
room is thinking.

00:15:51.910 --> 00:15:53.380
They're all sitting
here in bliss.

00:15:53.380 --> 00:15:55.240
They're all sitting here bathed
in brilliant white light.

00:15:55.240 --> 00:15:56.950
Or is that golden light, I
forget what color of light

00:15:56.950 --> 00:15:58.015
that's supposed to be.

00:15:58.015 --> 00:16:00.090
Some kind of light everybody
gets, but I don't have it.

00:16:00.090 --> 00:16:00.660
They have it.

00:16:00.660 --> 00:16:01.565
I don't have it.

00:16:01.565 --> 00:16:02.440
They're not thinking.

00:16:02.440 --> 00:16:03.040
I'm thinking.

00:16:03.040 --> 00:16:04.540
Maybe they are
thinking, but they're

00:16:04.540 --> 00:16:05.760
thinking beautiful thoughts.

00:16:05.760 --> 00:16:06.870
They're thinking
wonderful thoughts.

00:16:06.870 --> 00:16:08.300
That's because they're
wonderful people.

00:16:08.300 --> 00:16:09.424
I'm not a wonderful person.

00:16:09.424 --> 00:16:11.400
That's why I'm thinking
such stupid thoughts.

00:16:11.400 --> 00:16:13.170
I'm thinking such
petty thoughts.

00:16:13.170 --> 00:16:15.809
I'm thinking about the
traffic flow on 9th Avenue.

00:16:15.809 --> 00:16:18.100
Why am I thinking about the
traffic flow on 9th Avenue.

00:16:18.100 --> 00:16:19.914
I'm not responsible
for the traffic flow.

00:16:19.914 --> 00:16:22.080
And anyway, I wrote to the
mayor's office last year.

00:16:22.080 --> 00:16:23.790
You know, and it's just
like, why am I doing that?

00:16:23.790 --> 00:16:24.540
I'm so bad.

00:16:24.540 --> 00:16:25.260
I'm so useless.

00:16:25.260 --> 00:16:26.440
Right?

00:16:26.440 --> 00:16:31.960
So if we just engage in
that, if we fall into that,

00:16:31.960 --> 00:16:35.710
then not only have we extended
the period of distraction

00:16:35.710 --> 00:16:39.160
sometimes considerably,
but it's so demoralizing.

00:16:39.160 --> 00:16:41.950
It's so exhausting.

00:16:41.950 --> 00:16:46.340
We say in contrast that the
healing is in the return.

00:16:46.340 --> 00:16:49.000
Not in never having
wandered to begin with.

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:51.100
It's in our ability
to bounce back,

00:16:51.100 --> 00:16:53.650
to come back with compassion.

00:16:53.650 --> 00:16:56.190
With clarity.

00:16:56.190 --> 00:17:01.290
OK, so that's the basic platform
of the meditative process.

00:17:01.290 --> 00:17:06.210
And everything I talk
about in this book that

00:17:06.210 --> 00:17:14.490
follows that-- resiliency,
open awareness, integrity--

00:17:14.490 --> 00:17:19.180
we consider an emergent
property of those three.

00:17:19.180 --> 00:17:22.650
Concentration, mindfulness,
and compassion.

00:17:22.650 --> 00:17:26.720
That's how they get
developed in a real way.

00:17:26.720 --> 00:17:32.060
So that the platform is
really using these tools

00:17:32.060 --> 00:17:34.130
as a kind of skills
training, just

00:17:34.130 --> 00:17:36.510
like I learned way back when.

00:17:36.510 --> 00:17:39.120
It doesn't have to be
involved, needless to say,

00:17:39.120 --> 00:17:44.230
in a belief system, or a dogma,
or a certain kind of tradition,

00:17:44.230 --> 00:17:45.980
even.

00:17:45.980 --> 00:17:51.430
But just a kind of practical
application of these tools.

00:17:51.430 --> 00:17:53.470
I consider that a very
interesting moment

00:17:53.470 --> 00:17:56.140
too, because there
is a big difference

00:17:56.140 --> 00:17:59.480
between thinking about
them and doing them.

00:17:59.480 --> 00:18:02.620
It's of course so much
easier to think about them

00:18:02.620 --> 00:18:04.250
than to actually do them.

00:18:04.250 --> 00:18:07.160
There's something-- it's almost
like alchemy in that moment--

00:18:07.160 --> 00:18:10.230
where we're not deferring,
and we're not postponing.

00:18:10.230 --> 00:18:13.090
And we're saying, let me
see if this is true for me.

00:18:13.090 --> 00:18:17.940
It's like a grand
experiment that we make.

00:18:17.940 --> 00:18:19.680
One of the ways
this particular book

00:18:19.680 --> 00:18:26.900
came about for me was born from
a previous book of mine which

00:18:26.900 --> 00:18:28.470
is called real
happiness, which is

00:18:28.470 --> 00:18:35.150
like a template for establishing
a meditation program in one's

00:18:35.150 --> 00:18:35.690
life.

00:18:35.690 --> 00:18:40.060
And that book came out
a couple of years ago.

00:18:40.060 --> 00:18:43.080
And subsequent to
that, in February,

00:18:43.080 --> 00:18:47.200
we ran a challenge on my website
where people could sign up

00:18:47.200 --> 00:18:51.340
and we asked them to blog
or comment and describe

00:18:51.340 --> 00:18:52.730
their own meditation practice.

00:18:52.730 --> 00:18:55.370
And we asked everyone,
please be honest.

00:18:55.370 --> 00:18:58.745
Unless you actually sat down
and 10 seconds later you

00:18:58.745 --> 00:19:02.670
were floating away in a cloud
of bliss, don't say that.

00:19:02.670 --> 00:19:05.310
You know, lets really create
an authentic community

00:19:05.310 --> 00:19:07.990
by disclosing what our
experience actually is.

00:19:07.990 --> 00:19:10.980
So people did that,
and it was so beautiful

00:19:10.980 --> 00:19:14.020
and so interesting.

00:19:14.020 --> 00:19:16.660
And at the same time,
it seemed clearer

00:19:16.660 --> 00:19:22.760
that even given the wide variety
of occupations that people were

00:19:22.760 --> 00:19:26.470
engaged in-- from firefighters,
an undercover policewoman,

00:19:26.470 --> 00:19:29.730
and lots of tech people, and
school teachers, and nurses,

00:19:29.730 --> 00:19:34.610
and all kinds of people-- one
of the most challenging arenas

00:19:34.610 --> 00:19:40.590
to take these values and
make them real was work.

00:19:40.590 --> 00:19:46.210
So then I began to look at, OK,
let's say that you understand

00:19:46.210 --> 00:19:50.120
and practice some amount
of stabilizing attention,

00:19:50.120 --> 00:19:52.170
and refining attention
through mindfulness,

00:19:52.170 --> 00:19:54.890
and knowing how to
begin again, and having

00:19:54.890 --> 00:19:57.325
that deepening of
compassion-- what

00:19:57.325 --> 00:20:00.730
does that look like
in the workplace.

00:20:00.730 --> 00:20:03.740
What might it look
like, and how might you

00:20:03.740 --> 00:20:06.940
take that and make it real.

00:20:06.940 --> 00:20:09.090
So it's not just a nice thought.

00:20:09.090 --> 00:20:13.710
They say that the greatest
predictor of happiness at work

00:20:13.710 --> 00:20:15.884
is a sense of meaning.

00:20:15.884 --> 00:20:18.300
And that's very interesting,
because sometimes the meaning

00:20:18.300 --> 00:20:21.210
comes not at all from
the job description,

00:20:21.210 --> 00:20:26.570
but it can come from what
we bring to that job.

00:20:26.570 --> 00:20:27.760
How we are.

00:20:27.760 --> 00:20:30.190
First of all, there's a
sense of doing a craft well.

00:20:30.190 --> 00:20:32.890
Having great integrity
and fullness.

00:20:32.890 --> 00:20:37.420
In doing just the best
we can do at something.

00:20:37.420 --> 00:20:40.460
And it also comes from
any kind of communication

00:20:40.460 --> 00:20:41.950
and connection.

00:20:41.950 --> 00:20:45.840
Realizing that when we
relate to somebody else,

00:20:45.840 --> 00:20:47.530
whether it's a
colleague, or a client,

00:20:47.530 --> 00:20:51.920
or whatever it is-- that
is a meaningful moment.

00:20:51.920 --> 00:20:53.990
It's not just nothing.

00:20:53.990 --> 00:20:56.320
It's not negligible.

00:20:56.320 --> 00:21:00.270
And that we can use
that encounter, whatever

00:21:00.270 --> 00:21:05.020
it is, toward the
well being of not only

00:21:05.020 --> 00:21:07.830
a mission, but
that other person.

00:21:07.830 --> 00:21:10.710
And I find that with
any kind of job.

00:21:10.710 --> 00:21:11.950
It is really interesting.

00:21:11.950 --> 00:21:15.620
And I'll just close--
before we start

00:21:15.620 --> 00:21:19.050
sitting for a few minutes,
and then do questions--

00:21:19.050 --> 00:21:24.740
with what is, I think, my
favorite story from the book.

00:21:24.740 --> 00:21:27.670
And that is this time-- I love
telling this story in New York

00:21:27.670 --> 00:21:31.710
City because you don't need a
huge, long preamble about taxis

00:21:31.710 --> 00:21:35.170
and changes of
shift, but anyway.

00:21:35.170 --> 00:21:40.930
It was one of those hours when
it's so, so hard to get a taxi.

00:21:40.930 --> 00:21:44.100
And I was further downtown,
and I was on my way

00:21:44.100 --> 00:21:49.050
to Midtown, New York to try to
hear the Vietnamese Zen teacher

00:21:49.050 --> 00:21:50.950
Thich Nhat Hanh give a lecture.

00:21:50.950 --> 00:21:54.230
And it was just that time,
and I couldn't get a cab,

00:21:54.230 --> 00:21:56.780
and then a cab finally stopped.

00:21:56.780 --> 00:21:58.870
And of course the
lights were off,

00:21:58.870 --> 00:22:01.250
and they ask where you're
going, so that they

00:22:01.250 --> 00:22:03.280
could see if your
destination matches

00:22:03.280 --> 00:22:05.636
where they need to
drop off the cab.

00:22:05.636 --> 00:22:08.520
And so I told him, and
he said, OK get in.

00:22:08.520 --> 00:22:10.240
So I got in a cab,
and then we got

00:22:10.240 --> 00:22:16.850
stuck in the most unbelievable,
awful, unthinkable unbearable

00:22:16.850 --> 00:22:17.970
traffic.

00:22:17.970 --> 00:22:19.960
I'd never seen anything like it.

00:22:19.960 --> 00:22:23.990
And we were just crawling
along, going nowhere.

00:22:23.990 --> 00:22:25.475
And my first thought
was, oh great,

00:22:25.475 --> 00:22:28.110
I'm not going to
make the lecture.

00:22:28.110 --> 00:22:32.080
I then I really felt very bad
in terms of the cab driver.

00:22:32.080 --> 00:22:35.030
I thought, he was
nice enough to stop.

00:22:35.030 --> 00:22:37.060
His shift was over.

00:22:37.060 --> 00:22:39.400
I don't know if he gets
penalized in some way.

00:22:39.400 --> 00:22:43.290
I don't know if he has to
pay a fine in some way.

00:22:43.290 --> 00:22:46.690
And I said to him,
I am so sorry.

00:22:46.690 --> 00:22:48.280
It was really good
of you to stop,

00:22:48.280 --> 00:22:50.820
and now I've never
seen traffic like this.

00:22:50.820 --> 00:22:52.300
It's just unbelievable.

00:22:52.300 --> 00:22:54.700
I am so, so sorry.

00:22:54.700 --> 00:23:00.680
And he said to me, Madam,
traffic is not your fault.

00:23:00.680 --> 00:23:05.210
And then he said,
nor is it mine.

00:23:05.210 --> 00:23:06.990
And I thought, wow.

00:23:06.990 --> 00:23:08.540
First of all, I
don't have to get

00:23:08.540 --> 00:23:11.550
to the lecture, because I just
had an enlightened cab driver,

00:23:11.550 --> 00:23:16.360
and that was like my nugget
of wisdom for the day.

00:23:16.360 --> 00:23:21.450
And I kept thinking about that
second comment, nor is it mine.

00:23:21.450 --> 00:23:23.340
And I thought about
how many times in a day

00:23:23.340 --> 00:23:26.380
he's usually blamed for
something that's not his fault.

00:23:26.380 --> 00:23:28.760
Bridge is closed,
traffic's crazy.

00:23:28.760 --> 00:23:30.700
Some other driver
does something else.

00:23:30.700 --> 00:23:36.240
And I thought, what wisdom
not to take that on.

00:23:36.240 --> 00:23:37.830
And I thought, OK, there it is.

00:23:37.830 --> 00:23:42.810
There's an encounter that
was really, really important.

00:23:42.810 --> 00:23:47.120
So I think that's a
wonderful example of what

00:23:47.120 --> 00:23:49.975
we bring to any job
that we do, and how

00:23:49.975 --> 00:23:53.260
it can really make a difference.

00:23:53.260 --> 00:23:55.200
OK, so let's do some meditation.

00:23:55.200 --> 00:23:55.920
Is that OK?

00:24:01.080 --> 00:24:05.100
So, we say the essence
of meditation practice

00:24:05.100 --> 00:24:07.750
is balance, that's interesting.

00:24:07.750 --> 00:24:12.670
Instead of our normal,
maybe more acquisitive frame

00:24:12.670 --> 00:24:15.752
of mind-- like if I
have a big insight soon,

00:24:15.752 --> 00:24:16.710
I can get up and leave.

00:24:19.410 --> 00:24:24.490
The whole sensibility is that
the insight, everything else

00:24:24.490 --> 00:24:27.270
we want, will
emerge from bringing

00:24:27.270 --> 00:24:28.980
our system into greater balance.

00:24:28.980 --> 00:24:32.430
So they say some balance
is experienced right away

00:24:32.430 --> 00:24:33.400
in our posture.

00:24:33.400 --> 00:24:34.900
See if your back
can be straight,

00:24:34.900 --> 00:24:37.450
without being strained
or over-arched.

00:24:37.450 --> 00:24:40.570
You want some energy,
but not so much energy

00:24:40.570 --> 00:24:43.190
that you're really
rigid and uptight.

00:24:43.190 --> 00:24:46.030
You also want to be
relaxed, but not so relaxed

00:24:46.030 --> 00:24:49.670
that you're way slumped over,
nearly bound to fall asleep.

00:24:53.570 --> 00:24:56.510
And we'll start just
by listening to sound,

00:24:56.510 --> 00:24:58.780
whether it's the sound of
my voice, or other sounds.

00:25:02.790 --> 00:25:06.180
It's the way of
relaxing deep inside.

00:25:06.180 --> 00:25:08.615
Allowing our experience
to come and go.

00:25:14.264 --> 00:25:16.680
Of course we like certain
sounds and we don't like others.

00:25:19.500 --> 00:25:23.080
But we don't have to chase after
them to hold on, or push away.

00:25:23.080 --> 00:25:24.490
Just let it come, let it go.

00:26:08.300 --> 00:26:10.930
And bring your attention to the
feeling of your body sitting,

00:26:10.930 --> 00:26:12.370
whatever sensations
you discover.

00:26:43.560 --> 00:26:46.280
Bring your attention
to your hands.

00:26:46.280 --> 00:26:49.350
See if you can make the shift
from the more conceptual level,

00:26:49.350 --> 00:26:53.420
let go fingers, to the
world of direct sensation.

00:26:53.420 --> 00:26:56.250
Picking up, pulsing,
throbbing, pressure.

00:26:56.250 --> 00:26:58.495
Whatever it might be.

00:26:58.495 --> 00:27:00.620
You don't have to name
these things, but feel them.

00:27:27.950 --> 00:27:30.450
And then bring your attention
to the feeling of your breath.

00:27:30.450 --> 00:27:33.200
Just the normal, natural breath.

00:27:33.200 --> 00:27:35.710
Wherever it's clearest
or strongest for you.

00:27:35.710 --> 00:27:40.690
Maybe that's the nostrils,
or the chest, or the abdomen.

00:27:40.690 --> 00:27:43.067
If you find that place, you
can bring your attention

00:27:43.067 --> 00:27:43.900
there and just rest.

00:27:47.100 --> 00:27:48.630
See if you can feel one breath.

00:28:04.490 --> 00:28:09.250
If you like, you can use a quiet
mental notation of in, out--

00:28:09.250 --> 00:28:11.630
or rising, falling--
to help support

00:28:11.630 --> 00:28:16.460
the awareness of the
breath, but very quiet.

00:28:16.460 --> 00:28:18.110
So that your attention,
your attention

00:28:18.110 --> 00:28:19.790
is really going to
feeling the breath.

00:29:13.220 --> 00:29:16.750
And if images, or sounds,
or sensations, or emotions

00:29:16.750 --> 00:29:20.740
should arise-- but they're
not all that strong-- if you

00:29:20.740 --> 00:29:23.170
can stay connected to the
feeling of the breath,

00:29:23.170 --> 00:29:24.672
just let them flow on by.

00:29:24.672 --> 00:29:25.380
You're breathing.

00:29:28.680 --> 00:29:30.360
But if something
comes up with a bang,

00:29:30.360 --> 00:29:34.370
and it just pulls you away, you
get lost in thought, spun out

00:29:34.370 --> 00:29:37.220
in a fantasy, or you fall
asleep, don't worry about it.

00:29:40.980 --> 00:29:43.660
The most important moment
of the whole process

00:29:43.660 --> 00:29:46.146
is considered to be that moment.

00:29:46.146 --> 00:29:48.645
That's the moment we have the
chance to be really different.

00:29:53.310 --> 00:29:56.070
So instead of judging yourself,
and condemning yourself,

00:29:56.070 --> 00:29:59.890
see if you can gently let go.

00:29:59.890 --> 00:30:02.670
And shepherd your attention back
to the feeling of the breath.

00:30:07.230 --> 00:30:11.020
If you have to let go and
begin again, like 10,000 times,

00:30:11.020 --> 00:30:13.457
in the next few minutes,
that's really OK.

00:30:13.457 --> 00:30:14.290
That's the training.

00:32:49.010 --> 00:32:51.065
And when you feel ready,
you can open your eyes.

00:33:18.320 --> 00:33:21.420
So, we have a little time for
questions or comments, anything

00:33:21.420 --> 00:33:23.810
you'd like to talk about.

00:33:23.810 --> 00:33:27.670
And those two mics are there.

00:33:27.670 --> 00:33:31.410
If you can make your way over
there, that would be great.

00:33:38.159 --> 00:33:38.700
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:33:38.700 --> 00:33:41.210
SHARON SALZBERG: Hi.

00:33:41.210 --> 00:33:43.670
AUDIENCE: I have been meditating
for a couple of years now.

00:33:43.670 --> 00:33:44.669
Actually, things to you.

00:33:44.669 --> 00:33:47.840
I took some of your
classes at the Tibet House.

00:33:47.840 --> 00:33:49.850
And I find that I'm
still struggling

00:33:49.850 --> 00:33:53.060
with this very
basic thing, which

00:33:53.060 --> 00:33:57.240
is how to focus on the breath
without controlling the breath.

00:33:57.240 --> 00:33:59.530
And I've tried all kinds
of tricks, and some of them

00:33:59.530 --> 00:34:00.680
occasionally work.

00:34:00.680 --> 00:34:01.540
Most of them don't.

00:34:01.540 --> 00:34:04.906
And I wondered if you
had any thought on that.

00:34:04.906 --> 00:34:07.200
SHARON SALZBERG:
What are your tricks?

00:34:07.200 --> 00:34:10.219
AUDIENCE: One of them was to
focus-- instead of focusing

00:34:10.219 --> 00:34:14.760
on the most prominent
place where the breath is,

00:34:14.760 --> 00:34:17.400
to focus on something else
that's affected by the breath,

00:34:17.400 --> 00:34:19.269
such as, like, my
shoulders, and how

00:34:19.269 --> 00:34:20.560
they're affected by the breath.

00:34:20.560 --> 00:34:22.389
And then I don't control
it quite as much.

00:34:22.389 --> 00:34:24.870
SHARON SALZBERG: Right, OK.

00:34:24.870 --> 00:34:26.920
First of all, I
wouldn't worry so much

00:34:26.920 --> 00:34:28.310
about controlling the breath.

00:34:28.310 --> 00:34:32.889
It doesn't need to become the
major project of your practice.

00:34:32.889 --> 00:34:37.830
The reason we say don't
is more to counter

00:34:37.830 --> 00:34:40.820
the tendency we would have to
feel, well I'm not breathing

00:34:40.820 --> 00:34:44.010
deeply enough, properly,
appropriately, skillfully,

00:34:44.010 --> 00:34:45.219
whatever it is.

00:34:45.219 --> 00:34:48.080
And thereby making it a
breath exercise, rather than

00:34:48.080 --> 00:34:49.480
an awareness exercise.

00:34:49.480 --> 00:34:53.350
So, if you find that you're
controlling the breath somewhat

00:34:53.350 --> 00:34:55.770
and it's not exhausting
you, it's OK.

00:34:55.770 --> 00:34:56.780
Don't worry about it.

00:34:56.780 --> 00:35:03.430
A lot of what we talk about in
terms of controlling the breath

00:35:03.430 --> 00:35:06.160
is creating a kind of balance.

00:35:06.160 --> 00:35:09.630
So that would mean
spaciousness, openness.

00:35:09.630 --> 00:35:11.760
So that the breath
feels like it's

00:35:11.760 --> 00:35:13.930
happening in a bigger space.

00:35:13.930 --> 00:35:17.170
And so, people-- it is
like a personal experiment

00:35:17.170 --> 00:35:19.880
that people make--
just to see what helps

00:35:19.880 --> 00:35:21.740
create more that sense of space.

00:35:21.740 --> 00:35:26.080
For some people, it's as
simple as listening to sound.

00:35:26.080 --> 00:35:29.970
Which tends to be more
expansive in awareness.

00:35:29.970 --> 00:35:31.950
Or feeling your whole
body, and feeling

00:35:31.950 --> 00:35:35.580
the breath happening
within the body.

00:35:35.580 --> 00:35:39.060
It may be that if you're
mostly with the breath

00:35:39.060 --> 00:35:43.900
at the nostrils, that
switching to the abdomen

00:35:43.900 --> 00:35:46.789
will have a different
sense to it.

00:35:46.789 --> 00:35:47.830
So it's things like that.

00:35:47.830 --> 00:35:49.670
It's just kind of playing.

00:35:49.670 --> 00:35:52.550
Not with a sense of like,
I've got to correct this.

00:35:52.550 --> 00:35:55.530
But just to see if you
can create some balance.

00:35:55.530 --> 00:35:56.455
AUDIENCE: Right, OK.

00:35:56.455 --> 00:35:56.955
Thank you.

00:36:02.970 --> 00:36:07.340
AUDIENCE: Hi Sharon, thank
you for coming, or Salzberg.

00:36:07.340 --> 00:36:09.590
I've been meditating
for quite some time,

00:36:09.590 --> 00:36:13.870
and the example you brought
up about sending the letter

00:36:13.870 --> 00:36:16.860
to the mayor, and those
demoralizing thoughts-- one

00:36:16.860 --> 00:36:20.890
thing that I've practiced
