00:36:20.890 --> 00:36:23.510
My fear is that it
kind of gives you

00:36:23.510 --> 00:36:28.660
this sense of maybe false
value, or arrogance.

00:36:28.660 --> 00:36:31.512
Have you seen that happen
to people in the past?

00:36:31.512 --> 00:36:33.720
SHARON SALZBERG: So you have
those kinds of thoughts,

00:36:33.720 --> 00:36:35.994
and then you switch them?

00:36:35.994 --> 00:36:37.410
AUDIENCE: To very
positive, right?

00:36:37.410 --> 00:36:40.170
Like, wow, I sent a
letter to the mayor.

00:36:40.170 --> 00:36:44.710
Like, I have all this
power, or you know--

00:36:44.710 --> 00:36:48.120
SHARON SALZBERG: I don't
think that's a problem.

00:36:48.120 --> 00:36:51.400
I think ultimately all
those different methods,

00:36:51.400 --> 00:36:55.330
and the things we try, and the
tricks, and the ways we play,

00:36:55.330 --> 00:36:59.930
are all aimed toward creating
a more balanced relationship

00:36:59.930 --> 00:37:01.870
to our experience.

00:37:01.870 --> 00:37:05.850
And if that's what helps you see
the thought as just a thought,

00:37:05.850 --> 00:37:09.920
and not take it so to heart,
and not be so embroiled in it,

00:37:09.920 --> 00:37:12.200
it's great.

00:37:12.200 --> 00:37:15.020
The way I usually work
is more like-- myself,

00:37:15.020 --> 00:37:17.270
in my own practices.

00:37:17.270 --> 00:37:18.890
You know, sometimes
I tell the story

00:37:18.890 --> 00:37:24.950
about once having seen a cartoon
from the Peanuts comic strip.

00:37:24.950 --> 00:37:29.140
I saw it in a house that some
friends had rented for several

00:37:29.140 --> 00:37:30.740
of us to do a retreat
in, and it was

00:37:30.740 --> 00:37:34.430
left on the desk in the bedroom
that had been set aside for me.

00:37:34.430 --> 00:37:37.220
So, in the first
frame of the cartoon,

00:37:37.220 --> 00:37:38.722
Lucy is talking
to Charlie Brown,

00:37:38.722 --> 00:37:40.430
and she says, oh you
know, Charlie Brown,

00:37:40.430 --> 00:37:43.300
what your problem is--
the problem with you

00:37:43.300 --> 00:37:45.720
is that you're you.

00:37:45.720 --> 00:37:48.371
And then in the second frame,
poor Charlie Brown looks at her

00:37:48.371 --> 00:37:51.120
and says, well what in the
world can I do about that?

00:37:51.120 --> 00:37:53.240
And then in the third
and final frame,

00:37:53.240 --> 00:37:56.030
Lucy says, I don't pretend
to be able to give advice,

00:37:56.030 --> 00:37:59.130
I merely point out the problem.

00:37:59.130 --> 00:38:01.710
And somehow whenever I
was walking by that desk,

00:38:01.710 --> 00:38:03.950
my eye would fall
right on that line.

00:38:03.950 --> 00:38:06.980
The problem with you
is that you're you.

00:38:06.980 --> 00:38:11.160
Because that Lucy voice had
been so amazingly predominant

00:38:11.160 --> 00:38:13.120
in my earlier life.

00:38:13.120 --> 00:38:16.841
And I felt that one of the
techniques that I have been

00:38:16.841 --> 00:38:18.340
trained in, in terms
of mindfulness,

00:38:18.340 --> 00:38:19.920
is called mental noting.

00:38:19.920 --> 00:38:23.180
Where you quietly place a
label if the word comes easily

00:38:23.180 --> 00:38:24.720
on your predominant experience.

00:38:24.720 --> 00:38:27.470
So, I felt like seeing
that cartoon gave me

00:38:27.470 --> 00:38:31.480
a new mental note, which
was kind of like, hi Lucy.

00:38:31.480 --> 00:38:34.700
Or my favorite form of
that was, chill out Lucy.

00:38:34.700 --> 00:38:37.400
You know, something great
would happen for me,

00:38:37.400 --> 00:38:39.100
and my next thought
would be, it's never

00:38:39.100 --> 00:38:40.950
going to happen again.

00:38:40.950 --> 00:38:43.270
And I could say, chill out Lucy.

00:38:43.270 --> 00:38:45.340
You know, so it's not
like all freaked out,

00:38:45.340 --> 00:38:48.800
like Lucy's still here after
all these years of meditating.

00:38:48.800 --> 00:38:50.490
Or, yes Lucy, you're right.

00:38:50.490 --> 00:38:51.950
You're always right.

00:38:51.950 --> 00:38:54.390
But it's a very different
kind of relationship--

00:38:54.390 --> 00:38:58.320
of recognition, balance,
a little bit of space,

00:38:58.320 --> 00:38:59.780
a little bit of humor.

00:38:59.780 --> 00:39:02.420
Some tenderness,
some compassion,

00:39:02.420 --> 00:39:03.930
and an ability to let go.

00:39:03.930 --> 00:39:05.620
Like, OK, I see you.

00:39:05.620 --> 00:39:07.320
So that's one way of working.

00:39:07.320 --> 00:39:11.140
And if it works for
you to work with kind

00:39:11.140 --> 00:39:16.750
of molding the thoughts, or
seeing them in a different way,

00:39:16.750 --> 00:39:20.042
then that's just another
way of bringing balance.

00:39:20.042 --> 00:39:20.750
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:39:23.419 --> 00:39:23.960
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:39:23.960 --> 00:39:25.340
SHARON SALZBERG: Hi.

00:39:25.340 --> 00:39:27.480
AUDIENCE 3: I just
had a question.

00:39:27.480 --> 00:39:31.730
I've kind of been a meditation
dabbler for a number of years.

00:39:31.730 --> 00:39:33.890
But I've never had
a long term teacher.

00:39:33.890 --> 00:39:36.370
But I did have long
term music teachers.

00:39:36.370 --> 00:39:41.450
And I just wonder if
this instruction you gave

00:39:41.450 --> 00:39:43.735
is similar to instruction
I've heard elsewhere.

00:39:43.735 --> 00:39:46.210
And I guess I just
wonder, if you've

00:39:46.210 --> 00:39:49.450
been doing it for a
long time, or whatever

00:39:49.450 --> 00:39:51.330
your experience was.

00:39:51.330 --> 00:39:54.179
If kind of by analogy,
what we do now

00:39:54.179 --> 00:39:55.470
is sort of like playing scales.

00:39:55.470 --> 00:39:56.928
And then when you're
at your level,

00:39:56.928 --> 00:39:59.910
it's like you're playing
Brahms concertos or something.

00:39:59.910 --> 00:40:02.070
If it's like a really
fundamentally, amazingly

00:40:02.070 --> 00:40:06.140
different experience, or if
you could somehow speak to what

00:40:06.140 --> 00:40:07.630
the processes is like.

00:40:07.630 --> 00:40:09.838
SHARON SALZBERG: Yeah, I
mean in some ways I actually

00:40:09.838 --> 00:40:13.210
see the instruction as a
fractal, which fascinates me.

00:40:13.210 --> 00:40:14.760
Like, the very
first instruction I

00:40:14.760 --> 00:40:18.170
ever got, when I went to
India all those years ago,

00:40:18.170 --> 00:40:21.410
and began my meditation
practice, which

00:40:21.410 --> 00:40:23.750
was in the context of an
intensive 10 day retreat.

00:40:23.750 --> 00:40:25.710
Because it took
me awhile to find

00:40:25.710 --> 00:40:27.905
just the kind of practical,
pragmatic approach

00:40:27.905 --> 00:40:29.450
I was looking for.

00:40:29.450 --> 00:40:31.150
That was the first
instruction I heard.

00:40:31.150 --> 00:40:33.210
Sit down and feel your breath.

00:40:33.210 --> 00:40:34.650
And I was very dismissive.

00:40:34.650 --> 00:40:36.250
I thought, feel my breath?

00:40:36.250 --> 00:40:38.100
I came all the way to India.

00:40:38.100 --> 00:40:41.342
Where's the magnificent,
fantastic, esoteric technique

00:40:41.342 --> 00:40:43.050
that's going to wipe
out all my suffering

00:40:43.050 --> 00:40:45.280
and make me a
totally happy person.

00:40:45.280 --> 00:40:47.169
I thought, feel my breath?

00:40:47.169 --> 00:40:48.710
I could have stayed
in Buffalo, where

00:40:48.710 --> 00:40:51.060
I was going to school,
to feel my breath.

00:40:51.060 --> 00:40:52.930
And then I thought,
how hard can this be.

00:40:52.930 --> 00:40:56.500
And then I was like,
whoa, this is not so easy.

00:40:56.500 --> 00:41:00.180
So there's so much contained
in that simple instruction.

00:41:00.180 --> 00:41:02.710
Settle your mind in the moment.

00:41:02.710 --> 00:41:05.250
Realize you're
distracted, and come back.

00:41:05.250 --> 00:41:08.010
There's a huge
amount there that has

00:41:08.010 --> 00:41:12.620
ramifications and implications
for something so much bigger.

00:41:12.620 --> 00:41:18.860
So, in a way I'm still playing
the scales 40 years later.

00:41:18.860 --> 00:41:21.110
And another way, of
course my experience

00:41:21.110 --> 00:41:22.390
is completely different.

00:41:22.390 --> 00:41:29.100
I think I was so self-judgmental
in the kind of level of anguish

00:41:29.100 --> 00:41:34.290
that I experienced and
expressed when I was distracted,

00:41:34.290 --> 00:41:39.120
or I had an emotion I didn't
like and was very strong.

00:41:39.120 --> 00:41:42.660
And now it's much more
like, hey, chill out Lucy.

00:41:42.660 --> 00:41:46.400
Which makes a big difference.

00:41:46.400 --> 00:41:48.750
I think there's a
common trajectory

00:41:48.750 --> 00:41:51.740
that people go through
depending on what motivates you.

00:41:51.740 --> 00:41:55.560
In the beginning,
there's a trajectory

00:41:55.560 --> 00:42:01.370
toward greater and greater
inclusivity and compassion

00:42:01.370 --> 00:42:04.430
that's born out of wisdom.

00:42:04.430 --> 00:42:09.890
Like, it's not forced.

00:42:09.890 --> 00:42:15.220
It's not something that you
feel obliged to develop.

00:42:15.220 --> 00:42:16.500
It's just something shifts.

00:42:16.500 --> 00:42:22.500
So that even if you're
thinking about your job,

00:42:22.500 --> 00:42:24.910
there's just a
kind of recognition

00:42:24.910 --> 00:42:29.390
of how many other people need
to do their jobs in a good way

00:42:29.390 --> 00:42:32.740
so that you can do
your job in a good way.

00:42:32.740 --> 00:42:33.240
Right?

00:42:33.240 --> 00:42:35.770
That we're not so isolated,
were not so alone.

00:42:35.770 --> 00:42:38.060
That we exist as part of
networks, and patterns,

00:42:38.060 --> 00:42:40.900
and a bigger fabric of life.

00:42:40.900 --> 00:42:45.160
Or, my very favorite reflection,
which we could do right now,

00:42:45.160 --> 00:42:49.912
is how many people come
to mind as having played

00:42:49.912 --> 00:42:52.370
any kind of role in your being
here in this room right now.

00:42:55.771 --> 00:42:56.270
Right?

00:42:56.270 --> 00:42:58.860
Because we're all
here because-- myself

00:42:58.860 --> 00:43:02.700
included-- because of
conversations, and encounters,

00:43:02.700 --> 00:43:04.140
and relationships.

00:43:04.140 --> 00:43:06.310
And somebody gave us a
book, or someone told us

00:43:06.310 --> 00:43:09.760
about their meditation practice,
or whatever it might be.

00:43:09.760 --> 00:43:11.480
It's just layers, and
layers, and layers.

00:43:11.480 --> 00:43:13.640
So this moment in
time is actually

00:43:13.640 --> 00:43:17.240
a confluence of connections.

00:43:17.240 --> 00:43:18.660
As is every moment in time.

00:43:18.660 --> 00:43:21.570
And so, whereas in
the beginning that

00:43:21.570 --> 00:43:23.780
might have seemed like
an abstract notion

00:43:23.780 --> 00:43:27.940
to me-- because I saw it,
and saw it, and saw it, to be

00:43:27.940 --> 00:43:31.950
true-- then it's just, it's
just different in those ways.

00:43:31.950 --> 00:43:38.480
And so, one of things I really
love about meditation practice

00:43:38.480 --> 00:43:43.890
is the level in which
it seems to change us.

00:43:43.890 --> 00:43:47.720
Because it's not deliberative,
and it's not studied.

00:43:47.720 --> 00:43:53.350
In the sense that you're
not encountering a stranger

00:43:53.350 --> 00:43:57.440
and feeling disinterested, and
then thinking, well, you know,

00:43:57.440 --> 00:44:00.270
I just did an eight week
meditation class on compassion.

00:44:00.270 --> 00:44:04.650
And I really should
force myself to smile,

00:44:04.650 --> 00:44:07.210
and pretend to be interested.

00:44:07.210 --> 00:44:08.550
It's not like that.

00:44:08.550 --> 00:44:11.740
There's just shifts that go on.

00:44:11.740 --> 00:44:14.270
So that these things
come much more naturally.

00:44:14.270 --> 00:44:19.300
Remember when the Dalai Lama was
awarded the Nobel Peace Prize,

00:44:19.300 --> 00:44:22.080
one of my friends said,
giving the Dalai Lama

00:44:22.080 --> 00:44:26.200
a peace prize is like giving
mother nature an art award.

00:44:26.200 --> 00:44:29.740
But his level of
compassion-- I thought of him

00:44:29.740 --> 00:44:32.910
because I've seen him meet
many strangers, obviously,

00:44:32.910 --> 00:44:33.700
of all kinds.

00:44:33.700 --> 00:44:35.280
And he always
seems to be present

00:44:35.280 --> 00:44:36.901
and interested and caring.

00:44:36.901 --> 00:44:39.150
You don't get the feeling
he's sitting there thinking,

00:44:39.150 --> 00:44:43.440
oh God, not you.

00:44:43.440 --> 00:44:45.720
Not five more people,
I can't believe it.

00:44:45.720 --> 00:44:49.590
But I am the Dalai Lama, so
I better act like I care.

00:44:49.590 --> 00:44:53.870
There seems to be a very
authentic sense of presence.

00:44:53.870 --> 00:44:56.260
But he's the one that gets
up at like 3:00 every morning

00:44:56.260 --> 00:44:57.540
and practices for three hours.

00:44:57.540 --> 00:44:58.870
It didn't just happen.

00:44:58.870 --> 00:45:02.470
But the changes become embodied.

00:45:02.470 --> 00:45:04.930
They become more
natural in that way.

